
[1]glorify

   GLO'RIFY, v.t. [L. gloria and facio, to make.]

   1. To praise; to magnify and honor in worship; to ascribe honor to, in
   thought or words. Ps.86.9

   God is glorified, when such his excellency, above all things, is with
   due admiration acknowledged.

   2. To make glorious; to exalt to glory, or to celestial happiness.

   Whom he justified, them he also glorified. Rom.8.

   The God of our fathers hath glorified his son

   Jesus. Acts.3.

   3. To praise; to honor; to extol.

   Whomsoever they find to be most licentious of life--him they set up and
   glorify.

   4. To procure honor or praise to.
